instruction: Write a short story based on the following prompt:  You find an abandoned puppy hiding from the rain on your doorstep. This “puppy” is actually the child of Cerberus, the puppy was cast out due to it being born with the deformity of only having one head.
output_1:
I found an abandoned puppy hiding from the rain on my doorstep.
“Oh dear, what happened?” I thought to myself.
“I’m sorry, I don’t have a lot of time for this. I’ll call the pound”
I dialed the number of my local animal shelter and told the person on the other line what had happened.
“Okay, thanks, we’ll be on our way to pick it up” the receptionist said.
A couple of hours later, a man in a suit and a woman in a lab coat showed up to my house with a big box.
“Hi” said the man in the suit. “We’re here to pick up the puppy.”
“Puppy?” I asked.
“I’m sorry, the person on the phone told us that you had a puppy on your doorstep. We have one here in the box that we would like to give you.”
“Oh, right, I did have a puppy. He’s actually just around here somewhere”
I ran out of the house and started looking around for him.
“Where could he be?” I thought to myself.
I looked all around the yard but I couldn’t find him.
“He’s probably hiding in the bushes.”
I walked around the bushes and found him laying there on the ground.
“Are you okay?” I asked.
“Yeah” he answered. “What are you going to do to me?”
“I’m not sure” I said. “Do you want to go to the pound?”
“No” he said. “I want to go home with you”
“Well, the person on the phone said that we couldn’t keep it”
“Do you have a dog house?” I asked.
“No” he said.
“How about some food?” I asked.
“No” he said.
“What about a bowl?”
“Yeah, I have a bowl”
“Okay, let me get you some food”
I went inside the house and found a bag of dog food in the pantry.
I came back outside and gave him the food.
“Thank you” he said.
“Here, let me help you up” I said.
I grabbed the puppy and started to walk him to the car.
“Where are we going?” he asked.
“To your new home” I said.
“You’re not taking me to the pound are you?”
“No” I said. “I promised that I would keep you”

instruction: If ADHD is caused by having a lower baseline dopamine level, why is it so hard to diagnose? Can't we just measure dopamine levels?
output_1:
Dopamine is a neurotransmitter that affects a wide range of functions in the body, including:

* Movement
* Learning
* Emotion
* Reward

Low levels of dopamine can cause a condition called attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD), which can lead to problems with concentration and focus, as well as impulsivity and hyperactivity.

However, the cause of low dopamine levels in people with ADHD is not well understood. Some studies have found that people with ADHD have lower levels of dopamine receptors in certain regions of the brain, while other research has suggested that people with ADHD have higher levels of enzymes that break down dopamine, or lower levels of a protein that helps dopamine stay in the brain.

It is unclear whether these differences in brain chemistry cause the symptoms of ADHD or if they are just a symptom of the disorder. There is also some evidence that low dopamine levels are not specific to ADHD and can occur in other conditions.

Because there is still some debate about the cause of low dopamine levels in people with ADHD, it is currently not possible to diagnose the disorder based on dopamine levels alone. Instead, ADHD is typically diagnosed based on the symptoms the person displays and their response to treatment.

To diagnose ADHD, a doctor will conduct a physical exam and ask questions about the person’s medical history, family history, and lifestyle habits. The doctor will also ask the person to fill out questionnaires that assess their symptoms.

If the doctor believes that the person has ADHD, they will refer them to a mental health professional for further assessment and treatment. This may include a psychiatric evaluation, which will involve a mental health professional conducting interviews and administering tests to determine the person’s mental state.

In addition to evaluating the person’s symptoms, the mental health professional will also evaluate the person’s response to treatment, including whether they have shown improvement after taking medication for ADHD. If the person does not show significant improvement after treatment, the mental health professional may recommend further testing to determine whether they have a different condition or disorder, such as depression or anxiety.

instruction: How do remote tribes that have no new genetic material for thousands of years not die out because of inbreeding?
output_1:
Remote tribes with no new genetic material for thousands of years are known as isolated populations. Isolated populations are vulnerable to inbreeding. Inbreeding is a form of genetic hitchhiking in which individuals with deleterious mutations that are harmful at low frequency in a population can become concentrated in the gene pool of a small population, leading to higher frequencies of the mutations.

One example of this is the Icelandic population. After the Vikings settled Iceland in the 9th century, they imported only a handful of people from Norway. Over the centuries, they mated with native Icelandic women, creating an isolated population of Vikings. In the early 2000s, a study of the Icelandic population found that many of them had inherited a harmful mutation in the MC1R gene that is associated with red hair.

Another example is the Amish. The Amish are a conservative Christian sect that lives a simple life in America. Over the centuries, they have not adopted many modern technologies and practices. Their lifestyle has isolated them from the wider world, and they are an example of an isolated population. In the 2000s, researchers sequenced the genomes of 21 Amish and found that they had many harmful mutations that are associated with diseases and developmental disorders.

The fact that these remote tribes have not died out despite thousands of years of inbreeding is evidence that humans are able to adapt to their environment by evolving over time.
output_2: Tribes that are isolated from the outside world often have genetic diseases that are rare in the general population, but which have been passed down through many generations in the tribe.  These diseases can cause problems for the tribe, or even be lethal for some members, but they don't wipe out the tribe as a whole, because the tribe is so small that any one individual only has a small chance of having the disease, and also because some members of the tribe have genetic material from other tribes that they mixed with.

instruction: Does forcing people (employees, customers, etc.) to change their password every 3-6 months really help with security?

If you force users to change their password once a year or once every 3 months the attacker will have to use new tools to try and guess your password. If you force users to change their password every 3 months there are less chances of them being able to guess your password.

•   Require users to store their passwords in a secure location and not to share their passwords with anyone.

•   Restrict the use of weak passwords, such as birth dates, social security numbers, or names of family members.

By requiring users to create strong passwords and to change them regularly, you’re significantly reducing the likelihood that their account will be compromised. instruction: How close ethnically are modern Greeks to the ancient Greeks?

For instance, the modern Greek populations of Italy, Albania, Bulgaria, Romania, Moldova, Ukraine, Serbia, Montenegro, and Bosnia and Herzegovina are descended from ancient Greeks who settled there during the Roman Empire.
The Greek language, too, is quite similar to the ancient Greek language. Ancient Greek and modern Greek are both Indo-European languages, with ancient Greek being one of the oldest attested varieties of Indo-European. Modern Greek has changed somewhat over time, and it has also absorbed loanwords from various languages that have been spoken in Greece since ancient times, but the two languages are still very similar. As a result, most ancient Greek texts can be read with little difficulty by modern Greeks who are fluent in ancient Greek, and modern Greeks who read ancient Greek texts are able to understand them with little difficulty as well.

In conclusion, then, the ancient Greeks and modern Greeks are very close ethnically.

instruction: why are elementary particles structureless?

  * The Standard Model (SM) of particle physics does not allow for particles to have any structure.
  * Particles are observed in a process called scattering. When a particle collides with another particle, the colliding particles may change their velocity but they will not change their structure. So if you have a particle with structure, when it collides with another particle, the structure will change. But since the structure is changing, you can't use the information of the particle's original structure to predict the particle's new structure. So in this case, you can only predict what will happen if the structure does not change, which is that the particle will remain structureless.

The elementary particles that make up the physical world around us are generally considered to be structureless and massless. This means they have no specific shape or size, and they also have no mass. This may seem counterintuitive, but it is the result of the theories used to describe them. In the Standard Model, elementary particles are described as quanta of energy and matter. As such, they are fundamentally massless and structureless.

However, there are some exceptions to this general rule. For example, the Higgs boson has a mass, and it also has a specific shape. Other particles, such as the gluons, can have both a mass and a structure. In general, however, elementary particles are considered to be massless and structureless.

One reason for this is that it makes the theories used to describe them more consistent. Mass and structure are usually associated with matter, which is something that energy cannot be. By describing particles as massless and structureless, the theories are more consistent and predictable.

Another reason is that it makes the theories more elegant and simple. It is easier to describe particles as massless and structureless, and this simplicity allows us to make more accurate predictions about the world around us.

Finally, it also makes the theories more general. Mass and structure are generally considered to be unique to matter, so describing particles as massless and structureless makes the theories more universal. They can be applied to a wider range of phenomena, and they can also make predictions about phenomena that are currently unknown.

instruction: What are some of the commonly held misconceptions about any of the American Indian/Native American cultural groups?

## Commonly Held Misconceptions About The American Indian/Native American Cultural Groups

1. Some people believe that Native Americans lived in tipis. However, tipis were mainly used by the Plains tribes, not the Northwest Coast tribes. The Natives in the Pacific Northwest region of the United States and Canada mainly lived in longhouses.
2. Some people believe that Natives had no written language. However, some Native American tribes developed their own written languages. The most well-known written language is the Cherokee syllabary, which was used to write the Cherokee language.
3. Some people believe that Native Americans ate raw meat. However, most Native Americans ate a diet that was mostly composed of plants. Meat was mostly eaten as a supplemental protein source, not the primary one.
output_2:
1. The Native American people were always a nomadic culture, which makes their relationship to land today a complicated issue.  In reality, the Native American people were semi-nomadic in the winter and settled in the summer and fall.  It was this combination of semi-nomadic and settled lifestyles that allowed them to thrive for thousands of years.  Many people today still view the Native American people as nomadic, even though it is a misconception.
 2. The Native American people did not have any written language.  While the written language is not a part of their cultural tradition, they had a form of oral tradition that lasted for thousands of years.  They were able to remember and pass down stories, history, and other information that we find in today's written language.  Many people today still view the Native American people as being illiterate, even though it is a misconception.
 3. The Native American people were nomadic hunters and gatherers.  In reality, the Native American people had multiple food sources and a diverse agricultural base.  Many people today still view the Native American people as having only one food source, even though it is a misconception.
 4. The Native American people had no contact with the Europeans.  The Native American people had contact with the Europeans.  While the contact was not always positive, the Native American people were able to learn new things from the Europeans, such as farming.  Many people today still view the Native American people as having had no contact with the Europeans, even though it is a misconception.
 5. The Native American people were never a part of a nation or tribe.  In reality, the Native American people were able to form nations and tribes based on similar language, similar culture, and similar ways of life.  Many people today still view the Native American people as having been a group of individuals, even though it is a misconception.
 6. The Native American people were wiped out by European diseases.  While European diseases did play a role in the decline of the Native American people, the Native American people were already in decline due to over-exploitation of their land and resources.  The disease only accelerated their decline.  Many people today still view the Native American people as having been completely wiped out by European diseases, even though it is a misconception.

instruction: What is the best explanation of Newton’s laws?
output_1:
Newton’s first law states that “A body at rest will remain at rest, and a body in motion will remain in motion unless acted upon by a force”.
Newton’s second law states that “For every action there is an equal and opposite reaction”.
And Newton’s third law states that “For every action, there is a reaction and it is always in the opposite direction”.
output_2:
Newton’s laws of motion explain how forces act on objects and what effect they have on the objects.  They can be thought of as a set of rules that when followed accurately describe how objects interact with each other.  The three laws are:

I.   A body at rest stays at rest and a body in motion stays in motion, unless acted on by a net external force.  This law is also referred to as the law of inertia.  It simply means that if a body is not acted on by an external force, it will remain at rest or continue to move at a constant speed.

II.   The acceleration of an object is directly proportional to the magnitude of the object’s net force, is inversely proportional to the object’s mass, and is directly proportional to the object’s coefficient of friction.  This law is also referred to as the law of acceleration.  It simply means that the greater the magnitude of a net force acting on an object, the greater the acceleration of that object.  This law also shows that an object with more mass will have less acceleration when acted on by the same force than an object with less mass.  This law also shows that an object with more friction will have less acceleration when acted on by the same force than an object with less friction.

III.   For every action there is an equal and opposite reaction.  This law is also referred to as the law of universal gravitation.  It simply means that when one object exerts a force on another object, the second object exerts an equal but opposite force on the first object.  This law also means that when one object is acted on by more than one force, the sum of the forces is equal to the object’s acceleration.
